---
/*
 * S10FoundationBridge.astro — Foundation Bridge section
 *
 * Two-zone layout per Section.astro architecture:
 *   entry slot  — Eyebrow → BlurReveal(h2) → lead
 *   default slot — para → PreparedBundle → pipeline + 8-step list →
 *                  live-channels intro → two GlassCards → UpNextTeaser
 *
 * Background: void (cool near-black #0F0F13). Technical mode (azure eyebrow).
 */
import Section from '../components/sections/Section.astro';
import Eyebrow from '../components/content/Eyebrow.astro';
import BlurReveal from '../components/content/BlurReveal.astro';
import GlassCard from '../components/content/GlassCard.astro';
import UpNextTeaser from '../components/content/UpNextTeaser.astro';
---

<Section id="s10" label="Foundation Bridge" background="void">
  <Fragment slot="entry">
    <Eyebrow label="FOUNDATION BRIDGE" />
    <BlurReveal>
      <h2 class="s10__headline">Foundation is how we use the kernel. It is not the only way.</h2>
    </BlurReveal>
    <p class="s10__lead">Foundation (<em>amplifier-foundation</em>) turns text bundle files into running sessions. It is the Amplifier team's reference implementation: their opinions about how to use the kernel, packaged for others. The kernel does not need it. You could build your own equivalent.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <div class="s10__body">
    <p>Think of Foundation as a convenience layer. The kernel accepts a raw configuration dictionary and a set of module paths. Foundation saves you from writing that dictionary yourself. It reads your bundle files, resolves your module references, installs packages, and assembles the configuration the kernel needs.</p>

    <h3 class="s10__sub">PreparedBundle</h3>
    <p>Foundation's output has four parts: a mount plan (which modules to load, in what slots, with what configuration), a resolver (maps module names to file paths), the original bundle (preserved for reference), and package paths (for cleanup at session end).</p>

    <h3 class="s10__sub">The preparation pipeline</h3>
    <p>Foundation handles all the practical mess between a text file and a running session: creating isolated environments, downloading modules from registries, resolving version constraints, assembling paths. Eight steps, shown in the sidebar. The kernel never sees any of it. It receives a clean mount plan and a resolver.</p>
    <ol class="s10__steps">
      <li>Compile mount plan</li>
      <li>Set up environment</li>
      <li>Install dependencies</li>
      <li>Collect module specs</li>
      <li>Download/install modules</li>
      <li>Persist install state</li>
      <li>Create resolver</li>
      <li>Return PreparedBundle</li>
    </ol>

    <h3 class="s10__sub">Foundation does not disappear after setup. It stays connected through two live channels.</h3>
    <p>Most preparation layers do their work and leave. Foundation registers two callbacks during setup that remain active for the session's entire lifetime. The kernel calls back into Foundation code at runtime, even though the kernel has no dependency on Foundation.</p>

    <div class="s10__cards">
      <GlassCard>
        <p class="s10__card-title">System Prompt Factory — Called on every single turn</p>
        <p class="s10__card-body">Every time the AI is about to think (every single turn of conversation) Foundation re-reads all @mention files, resolves nested @mentions up to three levels deep, deduplicates content by SHA-256 hash, and rebuilds the complete system prompt from the instruction text plus all resolved context. This is why @mention files are live. The kernel calls a function and gets a string back. Foundation is the one doing the file I/O, all on every turn.</p>
      </GlassCard>
      <GlassCard>
        <p class="s10__card-title">BundleModuleResolver — Called on demand during loading</p>
        <p class="s10__card-body">When the kernel's Module Loader needs to find a module (to resolve a module identifier like <em>tool-filesystem</em> to an actual file path) it calls the resolver. That resolver was created by Foundation during the preparation pipeline. Foundation code is running inside the kernel's dispatch path, even though the kernel has no dependency on Foundation and no knowledge of how the resolution works.</p>
      </GlassCard>
    </div>
  </div>
  <UpNextTeaser nextSection="Agents & Recipes" teaser="Agents, skills, recipes: each one is built from pieces you have already seen." />
</Section>

<style>
  /* —— Entry: headline ————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s10__headline {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: var(--text-h2);
    font-weight: 600;
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
    color: var(--text-primary);
    max-width: 20ch;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* —— Entry: lead ————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s10__lead {
    font-size: clamp(1.125rem, 1.2vw, 1.25rem);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    color: var(--text-body);
    max-width: 55ch;
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 0; /* breathing room below BlurReveal */
  }

  .s10__lead em {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  /* —— Body ————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s10__body {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--text-body);
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  .s10__body p {
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }

  .s10__body em {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  /* —— Sub-headings ————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s10__sub {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--text-body);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    margin: var(--space-2) 0 0;
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }

  /* —— 8-step list ————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s10__steps {
    padding-left: var(--space-4);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-1);
    color: var(--text-body);
    font-size: var(--text-small);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
  }

  .s10__steps li {
    padding-left: var(--space-1);
  }

  /* —— Cards ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s10__cards {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
  }

  .s10__card-title {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--text-small);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }

  .s10__card-body {
    font-size: var(--text-small);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    color: var(--text-body);
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
